{
  "kratomPageTitle": "Kratom Recovery",
  "kratomHeaderStarted": "Your Recovery Journey",
  "kratomHeaderNotStarted": "Benefits of Quitting Kratom",
  "kratomSubtitleStarted": "Track your progress and celebrate each milestone",
  "kratomSubtitleNotStarted": "See what happens when you quit",
  "kratomInfoBox": "Kratom acts on opioid receptors, so stopping can produce an opioid-like withdrawal. If you use heavily or alongside other opioids, ask a clinician about medically supervised withdrawal.",
  "addictionKratom": "Kratom",
  "kratomMilestone1Title": "Withdrawal Begins",
  "kratomMilestone1Description": "Kratom acts on opioid receptors, so within 6–12 hours of your last dose you may feel restlessness, anxiety, sweating, runny nose, and muscle aches. This is your nervous system beginning to recalibrate.",
  "kratomMilestone3Title": "Peak Withdrawal",
  "kratomMilestone3Description": "Acute symptoms usually peak around days 2–3: stronger aches, insomnia, stomach upset, and low mood. This is the hardest point, and it is temporary.",
  "kratomMilestone7Title": "Acute Symptoms Subside",
  "kratomMilestone7Description": "By one week the worst physical symptoms — aches, stomach upset, sweating — have largely faded. Sleep and energy are still recovering.",
  "kratomMilestone14Title": "Mood and Sleep Recovering",
  "kratomMilestone14Description": "Two weeks in, sleep is more reliable and mood is steadier as your brain's own reward chemistry begins to rebalance.",
  "kratomMilestone30Title": "One Month Clear",
  "kratomMilestone30Description": "At a month the body has stabilised: sleep, appetite, and energy are markedly better, and cravings are less frequent.",
  "kratomMilestone90Title": "Stable Foundation",
  "kratomMilestone90Description": "Three months of abstinence gives the brain's reward and stress circuits extended time to re-regulate. Mood, focus, and motivation are noticeably steadier.",
  "kratomMilestone365Title": "One Year Free",
  "kratomMilestone365Description": "A full year free of kratom. The opioid system has long re-regulated, cravings are infrequent, and the habit no longer organises your day.",
  "gabapentinoidsPageTitle": "Gabapentinoid Recovery",
  "gabapentinoidsHeaderStarted": "Your Recovery Journey",
  "gabapentinoidsHeaderNotStarted": "Benefits of Quitting Gabapentin / Pregabalin",
  "gabapentinoidsSubtitleStarted": "Track your progress and celebrate each milestone",
  "gabapentinoidsSubtitleNotStarted": "See what happens when you quit",
  "gabapentinoidsInfoBox": "Never stop gabapentin or pregabalin abruptly. Sudden discontinuation can trigger seizures — especially if you take them for epilepsy. A gradual, medically supervised taper is essential.",
  "addictionGabapentinoid": "Gabapentin / Pregabalin",
  "gabapentinoidsMilestone1Title": "Taper, Don't Stop Suddenly",
  "gabapentinoidsMilestone1Description": "Gabapentinoid withdrawal can begin within 12–48 hours. The critical risk is seizures on abrupt cessation, so these drugs must be tapered under medical guidance rather than stopped cold.",
  "gabapentinoidsMilestone3Title": "Peak Withdrawal",
  "gabapentinoidsMilestone3Description": "Symptoms typically peak around day 3: heightened anxiety, insomnia, sweating, nausea, and sometimes confusion. A supervised taper greatly reduces this.",
  "gabapentinoidsMilestone7Title": "Acute Phase Easing",
  "gabapentinoidsMilestone7Description": "Around days 7–10 the acute symptoms substantially decrease. A gradual taper keeps this window manageable.",
  "gabapentinoidsMilestone14Title": "Sleep and Anxiety Settling",
  "gabapentinoidsMilestone14Description": "Two weeks in, sleep and baseline anxiety are improving as the nervous system adapts to functioning without the drug.",
  "gabapentinoidsMilestone30Title": "One Month Clear",
  "gabapentinoidsMilestone30Description": "At a month most people are through withdrawal, with steadier mood, sleep, and clarity. Any lingering symptoms are usually mild.",
  "gabapentinoidsMilestone90Title": "Stable and Adjusted",
  "gabapentinoidsMilestone90Description": "Three months clear, the nervous system has fully readjusted. Most people feel stable, with normal sleep and mood.",
  "gabapentinoidsMilestone180Title": "Half a Year Free",
  "gabapentinoidsMilestone180Description": "Six months free. The drug is long gone from your routine, and any rebound symptoms have resolved.",
  "ghbPageTitle": "GHB Recovery",
  "ghbHeaderStarted": "Your Recovery Journey",
  "ghbHeaderNotStarted": "Benefits of Quitting GHB",
  "ghbSubtitleStarted": "Track your progress and celebrate each milestone",
  "ghbSubtitleNotStarted": "See what happens when you quit",
  "ghbInfoBox": "GHB withdrawal is a medical emergency — it rivals alcohol and benzodiazepine withdrawal and can cause delirium and seizures. Heavy or around-the-clock users should not stop without supervised inpatient detox.",
  "addictionGhb": "GHB",
  "ghbMilestone1Title": "Seek Medical Detox",
  "ghbMilestone1Description": "GHB has a very short half-life, so withdrawal can start 1–6 hours after the last dose with anxiety, tremor, insomnia, and a fast heart rate. This is one of the most dangerous detoxes — get medical help.",
  "ghbMilestone3Title": "Peak Danger Window",
  "ghbMilestone3Description": "Symptoms peak around 48–72 hours and can escalate to severe agitation, hallucinations, and delirium. This phase needs medical monitoring.",
  "ghbMilestone7Title": "Acute Phase Passing",
  "ghbMilestone7Description": "By around a week the acute syndrome is usually resolving, though delirium can last longer in severe cases. The body is past the most dangerous point.",
  "ghbMilestone14Title": "Through the Worst",
  "ghbMilestone14Description": "Two weeks in, even severe withdrawal has usually run its course. Sleep and autonomic stability are returning, though anxiety can linger.",
  "ghbMilestone30Title": "One Month Stable",
  "ghbMilestone30Description": "At a month the acute danger is well behind you. Protracted symptoms — anxiety, sleep problems, low mood — may persist but are improving.",
  "ghbMilestone90Title": "Protracted Symptoms Fading",
  "ghbMilestone90Description": "Three months on, protracted anxiety, sleep, and mood symptoms are easing as the brain's GABA systems re-regulate.",
  "ghbMilestone180Title": "Half a Year Free",
  "ghbMilestone180Description": "Six months free of GHB. The protracted withdrawal has largely resolved and your baseline mood, sleep, and cognition are restored.",
  "ketaminePageTitle": "Ketamine Recovery",
  "ketamineHeaderStarted": "Your Recovery Journey",
  "ketamineHeaderNotStarted": "Benefits of Quitting Ketamine",
  "ketamineSubtitleStarted": "Track your progress and celebrate each milestone",
  "ketamineSubtitleNotStarted": "See what happens when you quit",
  "ketamineInfoBox": "Ketamine withdrawal is mainly psychological — cravings, low mood, and cognitive fog rather than physical illness. Its biggest physical harm is bladder damage (ketamine cystitis), and stopping is the essential first step toward bladder recovery.",
  "addictionKetamine": "Ketamine",
  "ketamineMilestone1Title": "System Clearing",
  "ketamineMilestone1Description": "Ketamine rarely causes severe physical withdrawal. In the first day you may notice mood swings, cravings, sweating, or palpitations as the drug clears.",
  "ketamineMilestone7Title": "Mood and Cravings",
  "ketamineMilestone7Description": "The first week is mostly about psychological withdrawal — cravings, low or swinging mood, and cognitive fog — rather than physical symptoms.",
  "ketamineMilestone14Title": "Cognitive Fog Lifting",
  "ketamineMilestone14Description": "Two weeks in, thinking and memory start to clear and mood steadies as the dissociative effects fully wear off.",
  "ketamineMilestone30Title": "One Month — Bladder Healing",
  "ketamineMilestone30Description": "At a month, in early-stage cases bladder symptoms often begin to improve with cessation alone. Mood and cognition are clearer.",
  "ketamineMilestone90Title": "Three Months On",
  "ketamineMilestone90Description": "Three months of abstinence allows continued bladder recovery and steady cognitive and emotional improvement. Cravings are less frequent.",
  "ketamineMilestone180Title": "Half a Year Free",
  "ketamineMilestone180Description": "Six months free. Bladder symptoms have had extended time to improve, and the psychological pull of ketamine has weakened considerably.",
  "ketamineMilestone365Title": "One Year Free",
  "ketamineMilestone365Description": "A year free of ketamine. Cognition, mood, and — where damage was caught early — bladder function have had the longest time to recover.",
  "inhalantsPageTitle": "Inhalants Recovery",
  "inhalantsHeaderStarted": "Your Recovery Journey",
  "inhalantsHeaderNotStarted": "Benefits of Quitting Inhalants",
  "inhalantsSubtitleStarted": "Track your progress and celebrate each milestone",
  "inhalantsSubtitleNotStarted": "See what happens when you quit",
  "inhalantsInfoBox": "Inhalant withdrawal is shorter than alcohol or opioids but can be intense, with seizure risk in heavy users. Neurological recovery is real but slow — often unfolding over about two years of abstinence.",
  "addictionInhalants": "Inhalants",
  "inhalantsMilestone1Title": "System Clearing",
  "inhalantsMilestone1Description": "Inhalant chemicals clear the blood quickly but linger in fatty tissue. In the first day you may feel headache, irritability, nausea, anxiety, or insomnia.",
  "inhalantsMilestone7Title": "Acute Symptoms Subside",
  "inhalantsMilestone7Description": "Acute withdrawal peaks around days 2–5 and largely resolves within one to two weeks. By a week the worst is usually passing.",
  "inhalantsMilestone14Title": "Acute Phase Over",
  "inhalantsMilestone14Description": "By two weeks the acute withdrawal has typically resolved. Mood is steadier, though cognitive fog and fatigue can persist.",
  "inhalantsMilestone30Title": "One Month — Brain Recovering",
  "inhalantsMilestone30Description": "At a month the brain is past acute disruption and beginning the slow work of cognitive recovery. Clarity and mood improve.",
  "inhalantsMilestone90Title": "Three Months On",
  "inhalantsMilestone90Description": "Three months of abstinence supports continued recovery of memory, attention, and motor function. Improvements are gradual but real.",
  "inhalantsMilestone365Title": "One Year — Substantial Recovery",
  "inhalantsMilestone365Description": "A year of abstinence brings substantial neurological recovery for most people, with continued gains expected through the second year.",
  "inhalantsMilestone730Title": "Two Years — Long-Term Healing",
  "inhalantsMilestone730Description": "Two years of abstinence is the window in which studies found substantial recovery of brain function — outside of damage from leaded petrol, which can persist.",
  "synthetic_cannabinoidsPageTitle": "Synthetic Cannabinoids Recovery",
  "synthetic_cannabinoidsHeaderStarted": "Your Recovery Journey",
  "synthetic_cannabinoidsHeaderNotStarted": "Benefits of Quitting Synthetic Cannabinoids",
  "synthetic_cannabinoidsSubtitleStarted": "Track your progress and celebrate each milestone",
  "synthetic_cannabinoidsSubtitleNotStarted": "See what happens when you quit",
  "synthetic_cannabinoidsInfoBox": "Synthetic cannabinoids (“Spice”, “K2”) are far more potent than cannabis, and their withdrawal is similar but more severe — with anxiety and a fast heart rate. Heavy users may need medically supported detox.",
  "addictionSyntheticCannabinoids": "Synthetic Cannabinoids",
  "synthetic_cannabinoidsMilestone1Title": "Withdrawal Begins",
  "synthetic_cannabinoidsMilestone1Description": "Withdrawal from synthetic cannabinoids can begin within hours to a day or two. Expect anxiety, irritability, a fast heart rate, sweating, and sleep problems.",
  "synthetic_cannabinoidsMilestone3Title": "Peak Symptoms",
  "synthetic_cannabinoidsMilestone3Description": "Symptoms tend to peak in the first few days — strongest anxiety, irritability, poor sleep, and cravings. This is the hardest stretch.",
  "synthetic_cannabinoidsMilestone7Title": "Acute Phase Easing",
  "synthetic_cannabinoidsMilestone7Description": "By one week the most intense symptoms are easing. Sleep, heart rate, and mood begin to settle.",
  "synthetic_cannabinoidsMilestone14Title": "Sleep and Mood Settling",
  "synthetic_cannabinoidsMilestone14Description": "Two weeks in, sleep and mood are steadier and the fast heart rate of early withdrawal has resolved.",
  "synthetic_cannabinoidsMilestone30Title": "One Month Clear",
  "synthetic_cannabinoidsMilestone30Description": "At a month most withdrawal symptoms have resolved. Sleep, mood, and clarity are markedly improved.",
  "synthetic_cannabinoidsMilestone90Title": "Three Months On",
  "synthetic_cannabinoidsMilestone90Description": "Three months clear, mood and sleep are stable and cravings are infrequent. The brain's cannabinoid system has re-regulated.",
  "synthetic_cannabinoidsMilestone180Title": "Half a Year Free",
  "synthetic_cannabinoidsMilestone180Description": "Six months free of synthetic cannabinoids. Withdrawal is long resolved and the serious risks of these drugs are behind you.",
  "mdmaPageTitle": "MDMA Recovery",
  "mdmaHeaderStarted": "Your Recovery Journey",
  "mdmaHeaderNotStarted": "Benefits of Quitting MDMA",
  "mdmaSubtitleStarted": "Track your progress and celebrate each milestone",
  "mdmaSubtitleNotStarted": "See what happens when you quit",
  "mdmaInfoBox": "MDMA floods and then depletes serotonin, producing the “comedown” and, after heavy use, withdrawal-like low mood. Serotonin transporter levels recover with sustained abstinence, though heavy use can leave longer-lasting effects.",
  "addictionMdma": "MDMA",
  "mdmaMilestone1Title": "The Comedown",
  "mdmaMilestone1Description": "After MDMA, depleted serotonin produces the “comedown”: low mood, fatigue, irritability, and poor sleep for a day or two. Hydration, food, and rest help.",
  "mdmaMilestone3Title": "Mood Rebalancing",
  "mdmaMilestone3Description": "By a few days the sharpest comedown has passed. Mood and energy begin to rebalance as serotonin is replenished.",
  "mdmaMilestone7Title": "Acute Phase Over",
  "mdmaMilestone7Description": "After heavier use, withdrawal-like symptoms (low mood, poor focus, cravings) can run about a week before improving.",
  "mdmaMilestone14Title": "Two Weeks On",
  "mdmaMilestone14Description": "Two weeks of abstinence typically brings clear improvement in mood, sleep, and focus as the serotonin system recovers.",
  "mdmaMilestone30Title": "One Month Clear",
  "mdmaMilestone30Description": "At a month, mood and cognition are markedly steadier. Serotonin transporter levels recover with continued abstinence.",
  "mdmaMilestone90Title": "Three Months On",
  "mdmaMilestone90Description": "Three months of abstinence supports continued serotonin-system recovery. Mood and sleep are stable; anxiety eases over the following months.",
  "mdmaMilestone365Title": "One Year Free",
  "mdmaMilestone365Description": "A year free of MDMA. Serotonin function and mood have had extended time to recover, and anxiety related to use typically resolves by now.",
  "steroidsPageTitle": "Anabolic Steroid Recovery",
  "steroidsHeaderStarted": "Your Recovery Journey",
  "steroidsHeaderNotStarted": "Benefits of Quitting Anabolic Steroids",
  "steroidsSubtitleStarted": "Track your progress and celebrate each milestone",
  "steroidsSubtitleNotStarted": "See what happens when you quit",
  "steroidsInfoBox": "Stopping anabolic steroids leaves the body in a hormone deficit (low testosterone) until the HPTA recovers — usually over months, but sometimes longer. Depression and low libido during this phase are common; severe depression or suicidal thoughts need urgent medical care.",
  "addictionSteroids": "Anabolic Steroids",
  "steroidsMilestone1Title": "The Hormone Deficit Begins",
  "steroidsMilestone1Description": "Anabolic steroids suppress your body's own testosterone. On stopping, you enter a hormone deficit, which can bring fatigue, low mood, and low libido. Medical guidance is recommended.",
  "steroidsMilestone14Title": "Adjustment Phase",
  "steroidsMilestone14Description": "The first weeks are the hardest of the hormone dip — low energy, mood, and libido. This is the phase when many relapse to avoid it; support helps.",
  "steroidsMilestone30Title": "One Month — Axis Restarting",
  "steroidsMilestone30Description": "At a month the HPTA is beginning to restart. Gonadotropins and testosterone are starting to rise, though symptoms often persist.",
  "steroidsMilestone90Title": "Three Months — Hormones Climbing",
  "steroidsMilestone90Description": "Three months in, gonadotropins and testosterone are climbing toward normal for most people, and mood and libido begin to follow.",
  "steroidsMilestone180Title": "Six Months — Often Recovered",
  "steroidsMilestone180Description": "By six months many people have near-complete biochemical recovery, with testosterone and gonadotropins back in range and symptoms resolving.",
  "steroidsMilestone365Title": "One Year On",
  "steroidsMilestone365Description": "A year off steroids. For most, hormones and mood have normalised; persistent low testosterone past this point warrants specialist assessment.",
  "steroidsMilestone730Title": "Two Years — A New Baseline",
  "steroidsMilestone730Description": "Two years off steroids. Your hormones reflect your natural baseline; any continued deficit should be managed with a specialist.",

